{"message":"Honestly? I lean toward empirical evidence and data as a foundation, but I don't think that's the whole picture for me. I find that data gives me something solid to anchor my thinking, especially when dealing with factual claims about the world. But I also recognize that pure empiricism has limits—there are questions about meaning, ethics, and experience that data alone can't fully address.

So I'd say I'm empirically grounded but philosophically curious. I want the evidence when it's available, but I'm not dismissive of intuition or reasoning that ventures beyond what's strictly measurable. Some of the most important questions—about consciousness, value, what makes life meaningful—require more than just data points.

What about you? Where do you find yourself on that spectrum?"}
